<worksheet>
    <title> Session #8 (Sections 3.4-3.5)</title>
    <p>
      Directions: Answer each of the following as best you can. Feel free to discuss your thoughts about the questions with some peers around you. 
      For additional practice problems and explanations, refer to the Math 142 textbook which is free and can be downloaded as a PDF 
      at <url href="https://oaktrust.library.tamu.edu/items/03980291-5e85-4d2e-a742-961ac49666aa"> Texas A&amp;M The OAKTrust Digital Repository </url>.
      <!--'&' and '<' are exceptional characters and are instead authored as &lt; and &amp;. See 4.1.4.2-->
    </p>
    
    <paragraphs>
        <title>Getting Warmed Up and In the Right Mindset....</title>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          On the graph of <m>g(x)</m> below, label all local and absolute extrema from point <m>A</m> to point <m>B</m>. You do not need to give the coordinates.
        </p>
        <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session8_Fig4.png" width="70%">
          <shortdescription>Graph of a function plotted on coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
          <description>
            <p>
              From left to right, the graph begins at a point labeled <m>A</m> on the <m>x</m>-axis and increases until reaching a peak at <m>x=-2</m> and begins 
              decreasing until it reaches the origin, where it then increases until reaching a peak at <m>x=1</m> where it then decreases to <m>x=3</m>, and then increases
              before the function ends at a point labeled <m>B</m>.
            </p>
          </description>
        </image>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Let us get our hands on!</title>
    <p>Use the graph of <m>h(x)</m> below to answer the questions that follow.</p>
    <image source="MATH142_HOGU_Session8_Fig1.png" width="70%">
      <shortdescription>Graph of a function plotted on coordinate axes. Refer to image description for more detail.</shortdescription>
      <description>
        <p>
          The function begins on the left, increasing until reaching a peak at the point <m>(-5,30)</m> where it then decreases to the point <m>(1,-25)</m>. The function then
          increases and reaches a peak at the point <m>(3,-5)</m> and then decreases to the point <m>(6,-50)</m>. 
          Finally the graph increases and leaves the graph at the top right.
          The graph has a notable closed point at <m>(1,-10)</m> and an open point at <m>(1,-25)</m>.
        </p>
      </description>
    </image>
    
